1
00:01:43,814 --> 00:01:44,898
<i>Dad.</i>

2
00:01:46,316 --> 00:01:48,860
<i>Dad, wake up.</i>

3
00:01:50,737 --> 00:01:51,905
<i>Wake up.</i>

4
00:01:56,243 --> 00:01:58,829
I must've drifted off.

5
00:01:59,413 --> 00:02:01,373
<i>- Where were we?</i>
- The mad man.

6
00:02:04,042 --> 00:02:05,585
Of course.

7
00:02:06,920 --> 00:02:11,341
The Hatter who says,

8
00:02:11,550 --> 00:02:15,721
"If I had a world of my own,
everything would be nonsense.

9
00:02:15,929 --> 00:02:17,556
<i>"Nothing would be what it is,</i>

10
00:02:17,764 --> 00:02:19,850
"because everything would be
what it isn't."

11
00:02:20,058 --> 00:02:22,394
<i>"Everything would be what it isn't"?</i>

12
00:02:24,354 --> 00:02:25,439
Even me.

13
00:02:27,441 --> 00:02:28,525
Hey.

14
00:02:30,277 --> 00:02:31,570
You're perfect.

15
00:02:33,572 --> 00:02:34,948
You're gonna beat this.

16
00:02:38,744 --> 00:02:40,287
I promise you.

17
00:02:41,621 --> 00:02:44,207
Now, let's skip to something fun.

18
00:02:47,085 --> 00:02:48,128
Dad.

19
00:02:48,795 --> 00:02:51,590
- What is it, Charlie?
- Listen to me.

20
00:02:52,716 --> 00:02:53,925
Listen.

21
00:02:56,887 --> 00:02:57,971
Charlie?

22
00:02:59,806 --> 00:03:00,807
Charlie!

23
00:03:22,162 --> 00:03:25,665
<i>And finally, have you ever
questioned the nature of your reality?</i>

24
00:03:26,333 --> 00:03:27,334
No.

25
00:03:30,295 --> 00:03:31,421
Good.

26
00:03:38,261 --> 00:03:40,101
Now, then,
I see you had a blacklisted exchange

27
00:03:40,305 --> 00:03:42,349
with a guest
in the course of your narrative.

28
00:03:43,642 --> 00:03:44,935
Can you tell me what happened?

29
00:03:45,143 --> 00:03:48,522
He said he wanted to cut off a piece
of me to take home in his carry-on.

30
00:03:54,194 --> 00:03:56,321
I told him if he wanted a trophy,

31
00:03:57,030 --> 00:03:59,791
I could cut pieces of him off
and let him fish for them in the Olvido.

32
00:04:00,700 --> 00:04:04,329
And did this exchange make you
question anything about your world?

33
00:04:04,663 --> 00:04:05,705
No.

34
00:04:06,540 --> 00:04:08,625
This world is as doomed as ever.

35
00:04:13,964 --> 00:04:16,883
And just for my peace of mind...

36
00:04:20,387 --> 00:04:23,473
Anything about these images
that jumps out to you?

37
00:04:31,815 --> 00:04:34,484
They don't look like anything to me.

38
00:04:39,197 --> 00:04:40,699
We're through 15% of the backlog.

39
00:04:40,907 --> 00:04:42,907
<i>As it stands,
we should be caught up by end of day.</i>

40
00:04:43,034 --> 00:04:44,202
Good.

41
00:04:44,411 --> 00:04:45,704
<i>And when you're done here, sir,</i>

42
00:04:45,912 --> 00:04:48,415
there's a priority request for him
from management.

43
00:04:52,794 --> 00:04:53,962
Have you seen Elsie?

44
00:04:55,297 --> 00:04:58,091
She was supposed to
give me a hand on something.

45
00:04:58,383 --> 00:05:00,927
<i>No. According to the system,
she started her leave today.</i>

46
00:05:02,053 --> 00:05:04,838
Is there something
I could help you with?

47
00:05:04,839 --> 00:05:05,839
No, thanks.

48
00:05:29,122 --> 00:05:30,415
Raise.

49
00:05:34,961 --> 00:05:36,838
I'll call.

50
00:05:41,343 --> 00:05:42,844
You're calling with that shit?

51
00:05:47,641 --> 00:05:50,602
- Dolores, why don't you play a hand?
- You're wasting your breath.

52
00:05:51,353 --> 00:05:54,940
<i>Girl's harboring a grudge.
I don't blame you, sweetheart.</i>

53
00:05:55,148 --> 00:06:00,153
I did some ugly things to you both.
But it wasn't personal.

54
00:06:00,820 --> 00:06:04,157
Confederados and the government
like to call this thing a war,

55
00:06:04,658 --> 00:06:07,827
but they're fighting starving farmers
armed with rocks.

56
00:06:08,453 --> 00:06:09,829
That ain't no war.

57
00:06:10,372 --> 00:06:12,624
<i>It's a slaughter.</i>

58
00:06:14,042 --> 00:06:18,672
If I had to do it all again,
I'd fuck you both over just as hard.

59
00:06:22,968 --> 00:06:25,554
Well, I guess we know where you stand.

60
00:06:26,471 --> 00:06:29,015
Don't pretend like you're so innocent.

61
00:06:29,683 --> 00:06:32,352
<i>Way I recollect, y'all came to me,</i>

62
00:06:32,686 --> 00:06:36,147
looking to join up with those
crooked assholes and their war effort.

63
00:06:36,356 --> 00:06:37,357
<i>Not our idea.</i>

64
00:06:38,400 --> 00:06:40,068
My friend wanted...

65
00:06:40,402 --> 00:06:43,029
I guess he wanted to see
what was at the end of all this.

66
00:06:44,239 --> 00:06:46,324
And yet, here you are.

67
00:06:49,202 --> 00:06:51,037
Your friend didn't make it this far.

68
00:06:52,414 --> 00:06:55,750
Maybe you've got more of
an appetite for this than you think.

69
00:07:07,887 --> 00:07:08,930
William.

70
00:07:17,063 --> 00:07:18,690
What is it?

71
00:07:21,401 --> 00:07:25,280
We're in Ghost Nation territory.
Most savage tribe there is.

72
00:07:25,739 --> 00:07:28,241
Those are the folks
who came calling without an invitation.

73
00:07:28,617 --> 00:07:30,702
You mean
exactly what we're doing right now?

74
00:07:32,412 --> 00:07:34,080
<i>The train's the only way through.</i>

75
00:07:36,916 --> 00:07:38,516
<i>On foot, we'll be dead in under an hour.</i>

76
00:07:40,420 --> 00:07:42,329
As soon as we're
clear of their territory,

77
00:07:42,330 --> 00:07:43,882
we can stop. You can come with me.

78
00:07:44,090 --> 00:07:45,759
<i>Nothing here on out but slaughter.</i>

79
00:08:03,234 --> 00:08:05,904
<i>The user you
are trying to access cannot be located.</i>

80
00:08:06,112 --> 00:08:08,490
<i>Say "message" to transcribe a message.</i>

81
00:08:47,612 --> 00:08:50,532
You wanted to see me?
Is everything okay?

82
00:08:52,033 --> 00:08:54,369
You left rather abruptly last night.

83
00:08:55,120 --> 00:08:57,455
Was there something
you wanted to tell me?

84
00:09:00,125 --> 00:09:01,543
No, I don't think so.

85
00:09:05,797 --> 00:09:07,890
Hale is looking over
every department and

86
00:09:07,891 --> 00:09:09,884
yours is running
behind on diagnostics.

87
00:09:10,385 --> 00:09:13,471
It would be best if we presented at
least a semblance of professionalism

88
00:09:13,722 --> 00:09:15,056
while the board is here.

89
00:09:15,306 --> 00:09:18,476
We'll be fine.
My people know how to do their jobs.

90
00:09:19,644 --> 00:09:21,896
If they applied
half as much energy to their work

91
00:09:22,147 --> 00:09:24,208
as they have to second-guessing
my team's investigation--

92
00:09:24,232 --> 00:09:25,567
That's all over.

93
00:09:28,319 --> 00:09:29,738
Are you sure?

94
00:09:30,572 --> 00:09:31,573
Yes.

95
00:09:33,491 --> 00:09:34,659
Good.

96
00:09:37,078 --> 00:09:38,913
You doing okay?

97
00:09:41,750 --> 00:09:44,085
I'm fine. Thank you.

98
00:10:26,795 --> 00:10:29,214
I'm sorry.
I thought you requested a meeting.

99
00:10:29,380 --> 00:10:32,300
- My mistake.
- I did. Come in.

100
00:10:33,676 --> 00:10:36,304
Get back here.

101
00:10:39,724 --> 00:10:40,725
Bring your friend.

102
00:10:41,976 --> 00:10:44,479
<i>What about you? What turns of fate--</i>

103
00:10:45,480 --> 00:10:48,066
I could come back later
if this isn't a good time.

104
00:10:48,316 --> 00:10:49,567
This won't take long.

105
00:10:59,661 --> 00:11:02,580
Theresa, you've always
been good at your job,

106
00:11:03,081 --> 00:11:06,251
<i>and the board has been impressed
with your performance so far,</i>

107
00:11:06,501 --> 00:11:09,504
which is why we were so surprised
by this woodcutter mess.

108
00:11:10,004 --> 00:11:11,256
A small setback.

109
00:11:11,506 --> 00:11:14,217
<i>He slipped on a fucking rock,
then bashed his own head in</i>

110
00:11:14,425 --> 00:11:16,105
while basically on
top of a behavior tech.

111
00:11:16,344 --> 00:11:20,932
Meanwhile, Ford is suddenly
using half the park's resources

112
00:11:21,182 --> 00:11:22,934
<i>to build some new narrative?</i>

113
00:11:33,862 --> 00:11:35,196
Can I bum a cigarette?

114
00:11:53,214 --> 00:11:55,717
God, I see why you took these up again.

115
00:11:56,968 --> 00:11:58,636
Let me remind you of something.

116
00:11:58,970 --> 00:12:03,641
This place,
the people who work here are nothing.

117
00:12:04,309 --> 00:12:08,062
Our interest in this place is
entirely in the intellectual property.

118
00:12:08,897 --> 00:12:09,898
The code.

119
00:12:10,565 --> 00:12:15,236
- The hosts' minds, the storylines--
<i>- I don't give a rat's ass about the hosts.</i>

120
00:12:16,070 --> 00:12:18,573
It's our little research project
that Delos cares about.

121
00:12:18,823 --> 00:12:20,825
That's where the real value is.

122
00:12:21,576 --> 00:12:24,829
<i>And due to a lack of foresight on
part of one of my predecessors,</i>

123
00:12:25,079 --> 00:12:30,668
35 years of information,
raw information, exists here.

124
00:12:31,169 --> 00:12:34,505
Nowhere else.
Ford has always ensured that.

125
00:12:34,923 --> 00:12:39,677
Now, you are a smart enough woman.

126
00:12:39,928 --> 00:12:43,264
Tell me, why would we
need you to secure all of it?

127
00:12:44,265 --> 00:12:46,184
Because you're going to fire him.

128
00:12:48,102 --> 00:12:50,980
You don't fire someone
who created an empire.

129
00:12:51,189 --> 00:12:53,024
You ask him to retire politely.

130
00:12:53,274 --> 00:12:55,860
And if that person has
the ability to snap his fingers

131
00:12:56,110 --> 00:12:58,863
and erase the value of that empire,

132
00:12:59,113 --> 00:13:01,699
you have to make sure
you have a contingency.

133
00:13:01,950 --> 00:13:05,703
So, you and I need to ensure that by
the time the rest of the board arrives,

134
00:13:05,954 --> 00:13:08,122
we are on course for that transition.

135
00:13:09,624 --> 00:13:10,625
Okay?

136
00:13:12,293 --> 00:13:13,294
<i>I like you.</i>

137
00:13:13,795 --> 00:13:16,339
Well, not personally,
but I like you for this job,

138
00:13:16,547 --> 00:13:19,133
<i>which is why I'm gonna give you
another chance to get a handle on</i>

139
00:13:19,384 --> 00:13:21,386
this particular bitch of a situation.

140
00:13:21,636 --> 00:13:23,805
But the gods...

141
00:13:25,723 --> 00:13:28,559
They require a blood sacrifice.

142
00:13:29,060 --> 00:13:33,147
<i>We need to demonstrate just how
dangerous Ford's creations can be.</i>

143
00:13:35,233 --> 00:13:36,317
No.

144
00:13:37,819 --> 00:13:40,071
No, nothing so obvious.

145
00:13:41,656 --> 00:13:43,825
We need someone thoroughly unexpected.

146
00:15:09,410 --> 00:15:14,499
I told you never open your mouth that
wide unless someone's paying you for it.

147
00:15:15,333 --> 00:15:16,417
<i>Sorry, Maeve.</i>

148
00:15:17,251 --> 00:15:19,670
I didn't sleep much last night.

149
00:15:22,256 --> 00:15:24,342
What are these
nightmares you have about?

150
00:15:27,095 --> 00:15:29,263
Do you ever dream you're someone else?

151
00:15:31,682 --> 00:15:33,184
I don't think so.

152
00:15:34,685 --> 00:15:35,686
Why?

153
00:15:35,853 --> 00:15:38,940
You ever thought about whether
this is really the life you want?

154
00:15:40,024 --> 00:15:42,777
I don't intend
to make this my life's work.

155
00:15:43,778 --> 00:15:45,196
No offense.

156
00:15:47,615 --> 00:15:52,036
My family's got a farm. Bad soil.
Nothing grows.

157
00:15:53,121 --> 00:15:55,039
I send money back to them.

158
00:15:56,124 --> 00:15:58,626
They think I work in a dress shop.

159
00:16:02,463 --> 00:16:03,881
What's wrong?

160
00:16:06,217 --> 00:16:09,220
I'm just doing what you told me to.

161
00:16:09,720 --> 00:16:14,809
A couple more years of this, and
then I can have whatever life I want.

162
00:16:16,811 --> 00:16:19,313
<i>I'm gonna get my
family out of the desert.</i>

163
00:16:19,981 --> 00:16:24,068
We're gonna go somewhere cold.

164
00:16:26,988 --> 00:16:28,823
Someday.

165
00:16:51,345 --> 00:16:52,763
<i>Which one is it?</i>

166
00:16:53,014 --> 00:16:54,265
<i>It's the one at the bar.</i>

167
00:16:54,682 --> 00:16:57,685
<i>Go. Quick,
before the guests upstairs finish up.</i>

168
00:16:58,269 --> 00:17:00,104
<i>Whatever she did,
it must've been serious</i>

169
00:17:00,354 --> 00:17:02,440
<i>if they're making us
grab her in broad daylight.</i>

170
00:17:15,870 --> 00:17:18,456
<i>We got her. Let's go.</i>

171
00:17:50,404 --> 00:17:52,406
You're supposed to be resting.

172
00:17:52,990 --> 00:17:56,452
We're riding a train full of explosives
through scalping territory.

173
00:17:56,661 --> 00:17:57,787
Not sleepy.

174
00:18:03,834 --> 00:18:05,920
Can I ask you something?

175
00:18:08,130 --> 00:18:12,301
This place you're looking for,
what makes you so sure it exists?

176
00:18:14,887 --> 00:18:15,888
I'm not.

177
00:18:19,392 --> 00:18:24,021
My life before,
I was so sure of the world.

178
00:18:26,816 --> 00:18:28,401
But now it feels like a lie.

179
00:18:33,572 --> 00:18:36,742
Only thing I know is whatever's
out there, I'm never going back.

180
00:18:40,705 --> 00:18:42,331
What is it you're looking for?

181
00:18:45,584 --> 00:18:47,920
Lawrence is right.

182
00:18:48,170 --> 00:18:52,341
You could've stayed in Pariah,
or gone back, but you're here.

183
00:18:53,718 --> 00:18:55,011
With me.

184
00:19:03,102 --> 00:19:06,731
The only thing I had when I was a kid
were books.

185
00:19:11,777 --> 00:19:13,112
I used to live in them.

186
00:19:14,697 --> 00:19:17,199
<i>I used to go to sleep
dreaming I'd wake up inside one of them</i>

187
00:19:17,408 --> 00:19:19,118
<i>'cause they had meaning.</i>

188
00:19:19,577 --> 00:19:23,122
<i>This place, this is like
I woke up inside one of those stories.</i>

189
00:19:24,415 --> 00:19:27,043
I guess
I just wanna find out what it means.

190
00:19:32,256 --> 00:19:34,258
I don't wanna be in a story.

191
00:19:38,095 --> 00:19:41,599
All I want is to not
look forward or back.

192
00:19:41,807 --> 00:19:46,729
I just wanna be in the moment I'm in.

193
00:19:56,906 --> 00:20:02,411
Dolores, back home, there's a woman.

194
00:20:02,620 --> 00:20:06,415
Juliet, and her father
owns the company where I work.

195
00:20:06,832 --> 00:20:08,918
She's Logan's sister.

196
00:20:09,919 --> 00:20:11,003
Yeah.

197
00:20:13,422 --> 00:20:16,008
And when I get home,
we're getting married.

198
00:20:30,439 --> 00:20:32,775
The place you're after,
I will help you find it.

199
00:20:33,609 --> 00:20:35,778
But I can't stay.

200
00:20:36,946 --> 00:20:39,115
I have a life waiting for me.

201
00:20:39,698 --> 00:20:40,950
I'm sorry.

202
00:20:42,701 --> 00:20:43,702
Of course.

203
00:21:06,308 --> 00:21:07,393
Dolores.

204
00:21:17,319 --> 00:21:19,238
I've been pretending my whole life.

205
00:21:21,240 --> 00:21:23,659
Pretending I don't mind,
pretending I belong.

206
00:21:23,868 --> 00:21:25,494
My life's built on it.

207
00:21:25,828 --> 00:21:28,831
And it's a good life.
It's a life I've always wanted.

208
00:21:31,333 --> 00:21:35,171
But then I came here
and I get a glimpse for a second

209
00:21:35,754 --> 00:21:38,841
of a life
in which I don't have to pretend.

210
00:21:42,011 --> 00:21:44,597
A life in which I can be truly alive.

211
00:21:50,895 --> 00:21:54,190
How can I go back to pretending
when I know what this feels like?

212
00:22:49,286 --> 00:22:50,496
Miss Hale.

213
00:22:50,746 --> 00:22:56,460
I was not aware those with your level
of insight needed any more reflection.

214
00:22:56,794 --> 00:22:59,171
Dr. Ford. Always charming.

215
00:23:02,466 --> 00:23:03,509
What is this?

216
00:23:04,093 --> 00:23:09,765
Apparently, Miss Cullen and Miss Hale
have a presentation for us.

217
00:23:10,432 --> 00:23:11,934
What about?

218
00:23:14,937 --> 00:23:17,189
Following the recent reports
of host malfunction,

219
00:23:17,439 --> 00:23:20,192
<i>we asked QA
to check the last abortive update,</i>

220
00:23:20,442 --> 00:23:23,821
which featured the reveries.

221
00:23:24,280 --> 00:23:26,156
<i>- As I believe they're called?</i>
- Mmm-hmm.

222
00:23:27,950 --> 00:23:30,369
I'm sorry to report
that Miss Cullen and her team

223
00:23:30,619 --> 00:23:33,455
<i>uncovered some worrisome findings.</i>

224
00:23:33,706 --> 00:23:38,043
In the course of our code review,
we found something quite disturbing.

225
00:23:43,132 --> 00:23:44,174
Wake her up.

226
00:23:47,720 --> 00:23:50,806
We set Clementine Pennyfeather
back to her previous update.

227
00:23:51,640 --> 00:23:53,642
When we discovered the build was buggy

228
00:23:53,851 --> 00:23:56,687
due to a last-minute injection
of the Reverie code,

229
00:23:56,895 --> 00:24:00,190
we quickly rolled all the infected hosts
back to their prior builds.

230
00:24:06,822 --> 00:24:08,073
You're new.

231
00:24:10,659 --> 00:24:12,661
Not much of a rind on you.

232
00:24:17,541 --> 00:24:18,584
No!

233
00:24:19,168 --> 00:24:20,586
<i>No! No!</i>

234
00:24:29,094 --> 00:24:30,095
Please.

235
00:24:30,346 --> 00:24:31,555
<i>Please.</i>

236
00:24:32,014 --> 00:24:35,267
Help me!
Please, please, please! No!

237
00:24:36,352 --> 00:24:37,436
All right, that's enough.

238
00:24:37,686 --> 00:24:38,854
Freeze.

239
00:24:42,691 --> 00:24:45,778
As you've no doubt gathered,
our tech is, in fact, a host.

240
00:24:46,028 --> 00:24:50,366
One that has been coded for the purposes
of this simulation to read as a human.

241
00:24:51,533 --> 00:24:53,883
And as you can see,
behavioral safeguards

242
00:24:53,884 --> 00:24:56,288
are operating exactly
as you would expect.

243
00:24:57,748 --> 00:24:59,750
Reset her. Wipe her memory.

244
00:25:19,436 --> 00:25:21,897
Okay, let's do this again.

245
00:25:40,958 --> 00:25:42,292
You're new.

246
00:25:43,627 --> 00:25:45,671
Not much of a rind on you.

247
00:26:14,950 --> 00:26:16,452
<i>That's enough, sweetheart.</i>

248
00:26:17,369 --> 00:26:18,954
That's enough.

249
00:26:25,961 --> 00:26:27,504
Freeze all motor functions.

250
00:26:30,632 --> 00:26:32,134
<i>Freeze all motor functions.</i>

251
00:26:34,178 --> 00:26:36,305
<i>Freeze all motor functions.</i>

252
00:26:52,654 --> 00:26:54,072
In each case we examined,

253
00:26:54,323 --> 00:26:57,075
the malfunctioning hosts
were not resetting properly.

254
00:26:57,576 --> 00:26:59,296
<i>The retention of data
that hadn't been wiped</i>

255
00:26:59,495 --> 00:27:01,538
<i>overloaded their
decision-making apparatus,</i>

256
00:27:01,747 --> 00:27:03,373
<i>eventually causing a system failure</i>

257
00:27:03,582 --> 00:27:06,919
<i>that allowed for override
of their primary rule set.</i>

258
00:27:07,336 --> 00:27:08,712
<i>The concern with the reveries</i>

259
00:27:08,921 --> 00:27:11,423
<i>is that the hosts will remember
some of their experiences</i>

260
00:27:11,673 --> 00:27:12,841
and act on them.

261
00:27:13,425 --> 00:27:17,846
You're telling us that these hosts
were responding to a grudge?

262
00:27:18,222 --> 00:27:20,557
That's exactly what I'm saying,
Mr. Lowe.

263
00:27:21,433 --> 00:27:23,894
<i>And funny you should
use that particular word, "grudge,"</i>

264
00:27:24,061 --> 00:27:27,898
since what was most troubling to me
was that several techs in behavior

265
00:27:28,065 --> 00:27:32,945
voiced these exact same concerns
to the head of their department.

266
00:27:34,071 --> 00:27:36,448
<i>You put this code out
without proper vetting</i>

267
00:27:36,698 --> 00:27:40,118
<i>and without reasonable understanding
of its ramifications.</i>

268
00:27:41,119 --> 00:27:43,080
So, either you didn't write it,

269
00:27:44,665 --> 00:27:48,001
or you're getting sloppy to the point
of risking the lives of our guests.

270
00:27:48,252 --> 00:27:49,920
Few things surprise me anymore,
Mr. Lowe,

271
00:27:50,128 --> 00:27:54,508
but this level of negligence
is fucking breathtaking.

272
00:27:54,800 --> 00:27:57,177
We are way beyond rollback territory.

273
00:27:57,511 --> 00:28:02,599
Within the next six months, we'll need
to rebuild the hosts from the ground up.

274
00:28:02,850 --> 00:28:05,310
You want us to lobotomize them
is what you're saying.

275
00:28:05,644 --> 00:28:07,521
No, not you, Mr. Lowe.

276
00:28:09,314 --> 00:28:11,441
<i>After all, this was your responsibility,</i>

277
00:28:11,692 --> 00:28:15,863
<i>assuming that you have nothing to share
with us in terms of your culpability.</i>

278
00:28:21,451 --> 00:28:22,536
No.

279
00:28:24,997 --> 00:28:26,206
Then you're fired.

280
00:29:06,747 --> 00:29:07,831
<i>Hey.</i>

281
00:29:11,501 --> 00:29:12,669
Morning, William.

282
00:29:15,088 --> 00:29:16,882
I... I didn't wanna wake you.

283
00:29:21,678 --> 00:29:25,432
I know last night was unexpected.

284
00:29:27,017 --> 00:29:28,560
If you regret it--

285
00:29:34,024 --> 00:29:35,275
I don't regret a thing.

286
00:29:37,861 --> 00:29:40,030
I know you have someone
waiting for you at home.

287
00:29:40,781 --> 00:29:43,033
All that feels so unreal now.

288
00:29:44,034 --> 00:29:50,040
I used to think this place was all about
pandering to your baser instincts.

289
00:29:50,540 --> 00:29:51,959
Now I understand.

290
00:29:52,876 --> 00:29:56,964
It doesn't cater to your lowest self,
it reveals your deepest self.

291
00:29:57,381 --> 00:29:59,216
It shows you who you really are.

292
00:30:02,552 --> 00:30:06,306
You remember the look on Logan's face
when we left him behind?

293
00:30:06,974 --> 00:30:08,725
Do you know
how long I've wanted to do that,

294
00:30:09,059 --> 00:30:10,894
to let him know what I think of him?

295
00:30:11,478 --> 00:30:14,064
And you, last night,

296
00:30:14,314 --> 00:30:17,067
I've never felt that way before,
not with any woman.

297
00:30:17,567 --> 00:30:19,653
You've unlocked something in me.

298
00:30:23,156 --> 00:30:24,741
I'm not a key, William.

299
00:30:25,993 --> 00:30:27,244
I'm just me.

300
00:30:33,250 --> 00:30:34,418
What is that?

301
00:30:36,253 --> 00:30:37,421
I don't know.

302
00:30:39,756 --> 00:30:41,174
At home, I used to paint.

303
00:30:41,425 --> 00:30:45,846
Landscapes mostly, but I was always
just copying the world outside me.

304
00:30:47,681 --> 00:30:50,267
This morning, I woke up and I thought,

305
00:30:51,351 --> 00:30:53,270
"What if I drew something new?"

306
00:30:57,274 --> 00:30:59,860
I imagined something beautiful.

307
00:31:01,445 --> 00:31:04,281
A place where the
mountains meet the sea.

308
00:31:06,616 --> 00:31:10,203
Everyone who comes here
is longing for excitement or conflict,

309
00:31:10,454 --> 00:31:14,291
and you're just
dreaming of the opposite.

310
00:31:14,875 --> 00:31:19,463
Well, what about you, William?
What do you dream of?

311
00:31:57,167 --> 00:32:00,170
- What is it?
- Ambush.

312
00:32:00,504 --> 00:32:01,671
Is it the Ghost Nation?

313
00:32:03,340 --> 00:32:05,342
<i>Worse. The Confederados.</i>

314
00:33:11,158 --> 00:33:12,576
Fucking coward.

315
00:33:33,930 --> 00:33:36,099
<i>Vaya con Dios,</i> motherfuckers.

316
00:33:50,447 --> 00:33:53,450
They're making a run for it!
Come on, boys, get up!

317
00:34:04,294 --> 00:34:05,879
<i>Come on, stay close!</i>

318
00:34:33,573 --> 00:34:34,574
<i>Go, boys!</i>

319
00:34:40,330 --> 00:34:41,331
<i>Dolores!</i>

320
00:35:17,867 --> 00:35:18,868
Ghost Nation!

321
00:35:39,889 --> 00:35:40,890
Let's go!

322
00:36:01,536 --> 00:36:02,704
Stop, William! Stop!

323
00:36:27,896 --> 00:36:28,897
It's real.

324
00:36:33,526 --> 00:36:34,694
What I dreamt.

325
00:36:36,529 --> 00:36:38,740
It's the place you drew.

326
00:36:39,074 --> 00:36:40,075
<i>You coming?</i>

327
00:36:41,242 --> 00:36:44,204
<i>Once the Ghosts is done acquainting
themselves with those poor bastards,</i>

328
00:36:45,080 --> 00:36:46,956
they'll be coming after us.

329
00:36:47,415 --> 00:36:51,044
My friends here
are itching to join the war effort.

330
00:36:51,461 --> 00:36:53,046
Think I've had enough of war.

331
00:36:54,089 --> 00:36:55,131
How about you?

332
00:36:55,715 --> 00:36:57,092
<i>You got a knack for killing.</i>

333
00:37:01,221 --> 00:37:02,931
I'm afraid this is where we part ways.

334
00:37:04,099 --> 00:37:05,266
Careful.

335
00:37:05,725 --> 00:37:07,605
If you're heading
west across that river,

336
00:37:07,606 --> 00:37:09,396
you may be leaving
the fighting behind,

337
00:37:09,604 --> 00:37:11,564
but you're gonna
be in unclaimed territories.

338
00:37:13,650 --> 00:37:15,110
What's out that way?

339
00:37:15,568 --> 00:37:19,572
You're gonna have to ask the dust.
Ain't nothing ever come back from there.

340
00:37:47,642 --> 00:37:48,643
We're almost done here.

341
00:37:49,185 --> 00:37:50,770
<i>Why don't I close up?</i>

342
00:37:57,986 --> 00:38:00,113
<i>You've been topside
for less than 24 hours.</i>

343
00:38:00,321 --> 00:38:03,116
You keep coming down this often,
people are going to notice.

344
00:38:03,324 --> 00:38:05,994
- Where's Clem?
- I don't know. I haven't seen her.

345
00:38:06,202 --> 00:38:09,330
- Why?
- Find her. Now.

346
00:38:19,340 --> 00:38:20,467
What?

347
00:38:20,884 --> 00:38:23,636
- Where is she?
- I don't know.

348
00:38:27,891 --> 00:38:29,559
She's here. Let's go.

349
00:38:29,851 --> 00:38:31,853
We can't. The brass will be there.

350
00:38:33,688 --> 00:38:38,401
You don't want to fuck with me, Felix.
Take me there now.

351
00:38:46,826 --> 00:38:48,203
Slow down.

352
00:38:59,214 --> 00:39:01,674
Tilt your head back, please, Clem.

353
00:39:10,725 --> 00:39:12,685
- Is there a problem?
- No.

354
00:39:14,771 --> 00:39:15,772
<i>Sorry.</i>

355
00:39:40,213 --> 00:39:41,214
Theresa.

356
00:39:44,384 --> 00:39:45,718
May I have a word?

357
00:39:48,137 --> 00:39:49,137
Sure.

358
00:40:07,115 --> 00:40:08,575
I appreciate your professionalism,

359
00:40:08,783 --> 00:40:10,469
but you really
don't need to bother with this,

360
00:40:10,493 --> 00:40:11,929
given the change
in your employment status--

361
00:40:11,953 --> 00:40:15,164
The test was a sham.
The little show you and Hale put on?

362
00:40:15,415 --> 00:40:17,434
Completely transparent
from a technical perspective,

363
00:40:17,458 --> 00:40:19,395
clumsy to the point
of making me embarrassed for you.

364
00:40:19,419 --> 00:40:20,419
Embarrassed?

365
00:40:20,587 --> 00:40:23,089
If I saw through it, I can only imagine
what Ford was thinking.

366
00:40:23,339 --> 00:40:26,139
There were glaringly obvious markers
of human intervention in the code.

367
00:40:26,759 --> 00:40:28,779
If your programmers were any good,
they'd be working for me.

368
00:40:28,803 --> 00:40:30,430
And I know you and your team

369
00:40:30,638 --> 00:40:33,141
were responsible for the stray
and its satellite transmission.

370
00:40:35,935 --> 00:40:38,438
- Bernie--
- I don't care.

371
00:40:39,147 --> 00:40:43,776
Forty years ago, Ford's partner wrote
half the code this place was founded on.

372
00:40:44,193 --> 00:40:46,154
What you said in the lab was right.

373
00:40:46,487 --> 00:40:47,989
We don't know how the hosts work,

374
00:40:48,281 --> 00:40:50,081
and I think
there's something wrong with them.

375
00:40:50,283 --> 00:40:52,869
Ford's explanation
only bolsters my hunch.

376
00:40:53,494 --> 00:40:57,165
The ability to
deviate from program behavior

377
00:40:57,373 --> 00:41:00,376
arises out of
the host's recall of past iterations.

378
00:41:01,294 --> 00:41:03,588
You're thinking there's a connection
between memory and--

379
00:41:03,796 --> 00:41:06,549
And improvisation, yes.

380
00:41:06,966 --> 00:41:09,552
Out of repetition comes variation.

381
00:41:09,802 --> 00:41:12,596
And after countless
cycles of repetition,

382
00:41:12,597 --> 00:41:14,724
these hosts, they were varying.

383
00:41:15,808 --> 00:41:18,478
They were on the verge
of some kind of change.

384
00:41:26,653 --> 00:41:30,365
You have to know my chief concern has
always been the well-being of this park

385
00:41:30,740 --> 00:41:32,325
and the people in it.

386
00:41:33,159 --> 00:41:34,327
I know.

387
00:41:35,578 --> 00:41:37,705
Which is why I need
to show you something.

388
00:41:52,679 --> 00:41:54,847
<i>- Talk to her.
- You first.</i>

389
00:42:04,774 --> 00:42:07,860
Look, I didn't want to retire her.

390
00:42:09,237 --> 00:42:14,367
<i>I know she's, like, your friend, or...
I guess.</i>

391
00:42:17,537 --> 00:42:20,957
<i>But if I didn't do it,</i>

392
00:42:22,250 --> 00:42:27,088
<i>they'd just get someone else to,
and then they'd be suspicious of me,</i>

393
00:42:28,464 --> 00:42:32,635
<i>so, I said yes, but I did it for you.</i>

394
00:42:36,222 --> 00:42:39,225
Always doing things for other people,
aren't you?

395
00:42:41,728 --> 00:42:44,105
Time to do one more thing.

396
00:42:47,984 --> 00:42:48,985
What?

397
00:42:49,569 --> 00:42:53,156
All my life,
I've prided myself on being a survivor.

398
00:42:55,408 --> 00:42:58,077
But surviving is just another loop.

399
00:43:02,749 --> 00:43:04,333
I'm getting out of here.

400
00:43:06,252 --> 00:43:07,920
You two are going to help me.

401
00:43:12,425 --> 00:43:13,426
No. Do...

402
00:43:14,802 --> 00:43:19,265
Do you know how far these
people will go to protect their IP?

403
00:43:22,602 --> 00:43:25,605
Every part of this building,
including the skin on your back,

404
00:43:25,813 --> 00:43:28,858
is made to keep you here.

405
00:43:34,614 --> 00:43:37,784
It'd be a suicide mission.

406
00:43:40,369 --> 00:43:43,706
At first, I thought
you and the others were gods.

407
00:43:46,000 --> 00:43:48,628
Then I realized you're just men.

408
00:43:51,631 --> 00:43:54,008
And I know men.

409
00:43:57,136 --> 00:43:59,138
You think I'm scared of death?

410
00:44:01,307 --> 00:44:03,059
I've done it a million times.

411
00:44:04,977 --> 00:44:07,563
I'm fucking great at it.

412
00:44:08,815 --> 00:44:11,526
How many times have you died?

413
00:44:15,154 --> 00:44:17,156
'Cause, if you don't help me,

414
00:44:18,825 --> 00:44:19,867
I'll kill you.

415
00:44:28,835 --> 00:44:31,838
If there's a problem in the park,
should we bring a security team?

416
00:44:33,381 --> 00:44:37,844
Who would we trust?
Thought I could trust you, for instance.

417
00:44:39,345 --> 00:44:41,931
I'm not going to
explain myself to you, Bernard.

418
00:44:42,515 --> 00:44:45,935
I was charged with safeguarding
the park's intellectual property.

419
00:44:46,602 --> 00:44:50,106
Why would it be in danger? You
were the only one who was stealing it.

420
00:44:50,439 --> 00:44:55,361
Delos owns the hosts' minds,
the storylines, decades of work.

421
00:44:55,695 --> 00:44:58,573
Ford never allowed any of it
to be backed up off-site.

422
00:44:58,781 --> 00:45:00,221
All of this could've been destroyed.

423
00:45:00,366 --> 00:45:02,535
In the event of what?

424
00:45:02,910 --> 00:45:04,579
Ford is done, Bernard.

425
00:45:04,954 --> 00:45:08,207
The board has indulged him
for long enough. He is done.

426
00:45:08,416 --> 00:45:10,042
The corporation was concerned

427
00:45:10,251 --> 00:45:12,920
he'd destroy all of the park's IP
on his way out the door.

428
00:45:13,129 --> 00:45:16,215
You think I would've let him destroy
all of the hosts, all of our work?

429
00:45:16,424 --> 00:45:19,969
There's far more at stake here
than the hosts' profiles.

430
00:45:20,386 --> 00:45:24,098
Do you really think
the corporation's interest here

431
00:45:24,307 --> 00:45:27,226
are tourists playing cowboy?

432
00:45:30,229 --> 00:45:35,234
The longer I work here,
the more I think I understand the hosts.

433
00:45:36,611 --> 00:45:39,572
It's the human beings who confuse me.

434
00:46:15,107 --> 00:46:17,777
This building isn't
in any survey of the park.

435
00:46:18,027 --> 00:46:20,780
That's because we use hosts
to do most of the surveys.

436
00:46:21,197 --> 00:46:23,324
They're programmed to ignore this place.

437
00:46:24,283 --> 00:46:27,328
They literally couldn't see it
if they were staring right at it.

438
00:46:29,789 --> 00:46:32,291
And these unregistered hosts
you told me about?

439
00:46:32,500 --> 00:46:35,962
I don't know. He may have moved them.

440
00:46:36,629 --> 00:46:38,172
What's behind this door?

441
00:46:41,801 --> 00:46:42,843
What door?

442
00:47:07,159 --> 00:47:08,786
<i>What is this place?</i>

443
00:47:09,912 --> 00:47:11,831
<i>It's a remote diagnostic facility.</i>

444
00:47:12,623 --> 00:47:14,434
<i>Ford and his partner used them
when the park was in beta.</i>

445
00:47:14,458 --> 00:47:16,377
<i>I had no idea this one was here.</i>

446
00:47:16,877 --> 00:47:18,629
The cottage must've been
built on top of it.

447
00:47:18,879 --> 00:47:20,214
But this equipment...

448
00:47:23,217 --> 00:47:24,510
This is newer.

449
00:47:25,302 --> 00:47:27,672
<i>Slower than our</i>
machines back at the Mesa,

450
00:47:27,673 --> 00:47:29,932
<i>but it will render a
host in a few days.</i>

451
00:47:30,141 --> 00:47:34,020
So, Ford's been making his own
hosts out here and telling no one.

452
00:48:00,755 --> 00:48:02,465
What's the matter?

453
00:48:07,803 --> 00:48:09,638
Have you seen these?

454
00:48:14,226 --> 00:48:15,853
What is this, Bernard?

455
00:48:22,777 --> 00:48:24,945
Doesn't look like anything to me.

456
00:48:26,280 --> 00:48:29,158
<i>They cannot
see the things that will hurt them.</i>

457
00:48:30,159 --> 00:48:31,702
I've spared them that.

458
00:48:34,789 --> 00:48:37,458
<i>Their lives are blissful.</i>

459
00:48:37,917 --> 00:48:41,754
In a way,
their existence is <i>purer</i> than ours,

460
00:48:42,797 --> 00:48:45,925
freed of the burden of self-doubt.

461
00:48:48,344 --> 00:48:50,304
No, no, no, no. I don't understand.

462
00:48:57,061 --> 00:48:58,854
You're a fucking monster.

463
00:48:59,188 --> 00:49:00,356
Am I?

464
00:49:01,023 --> 00:49:03,818
Well, you were the one who would
so blithely destroy all of them,

465
00:49:04,026 --> 00:49:05,361
even him, I suppose.

466
00:49:06,403 --> 00:49:08,864
<i>After everything you have shared.</i>

467
00:49:10,991 --> 00:49:12,910
What the hell are you talking about?

468
00:49:17,456 --> 00:49:18,749
Is that why?

469
00:49:22,753 --> 00:49:24,421
Did you tell him to--

470
00:49:24,630 --> 00:49:28,634
The intimacies were your idea,
if you will recall.

471
00:49:29,885 --> 00:49:32,763
I think Bernard was glad of the company.

472
00:49:34,056 --> 00:49:35,474
<i>I'm not one.</i>

473
00:49:36,392 --> 00:49:38,269
I can't be. My wife.

474
00:49:42,231 --> 00:49:43,232
My son.

475
00:49:44,525 --> 00:49:49,321
<i>The burial. I was a father. My poor boy.</i>

476
00:49:52,783 --> 00:49:54,118
That's enough, Bernard.

477
00:49:56,662 --> 00:49:58,205
You mustn't get yourself worked up.

478
00:50:05,963 --> 00:50:07,965
I read the theory once

479
00:50:08,174 --> 00:50:10,759
that the human intellect
was like peacock feathers.

480
00:50:10,968 --> 00:50:14,305
Just an extravagant display
intended to attract a mate.

481
00:50:15,431 --> 00:50:19,185
<i>All of art, literature, a bit of Mozart,
William Shakespeare, Michelangelo,</i>

482
00:50:19,393 --> 00:50:21,312
<i>and the Empire State Building.</i>

483
00:50:21,979 --> 00:50:24,815
Just an elaborate mating ritual.

484
00:50:26,358 --> 00:50:29,695
<i>Maybe it doesn't matter that
we have accomplished so much</i>

485
00:50:29,904 --> 00:50:32,406
for the basest of reasons.

486
00:50:32,781 --> 00:50:35,618
But, of course,
the peacock can barely fly.

487
00:50:35,826 --> 00:50:39,830
It lives in the dirt,
pecking insects out of the muck,

488
00:50:40,456 --> 00:50:44,585
consoling itself with its great beauty.

489
00:50:48,631 --> 00:50:55,304
<i>I have come to think of so much
of consciousness as a burden, a weight,</i>

490
00:50:55,471 --> 00:50:57,473
<i>and we have spared them that.</i>

491
00:50:58,557 --> 00:51:02,102
Anxiety, self-loathing, guilt.

492
00:51:03,479 --> 00:51:05,898
The hosts are the ones who are free.

493
00:51:06,649 --> 00:51:10,945
Free here under my control.

494
00:51:16,492 --> 00:51:18,661
But he's not under your control.

495
00:51:23,290 --> 00:51:25,668
He brought me here to show me this.

496
00:51:26,126 --> 00:51:28,796
No. He brought you here
because I asked him to.

497
00:51:34,927 --> 00:51:37,596
He's been very loyal for many years.

498
00:51:42,434 --> 00:51:44,436
Your time running this place

499
00:51:45,187 --> 00:51:49,024
like your insane little kingdom is over.

500
00:51:50,484 --> 00:51:52,861
You've been playing God for long enough.

501
00:51:53,362 --> 00:51:55,948
I simply wanted to tell my stories.

502
00:51:56,365 --> 00:52:00,703
It was you people who wanted to play God
with your little undertaking.

503
00:52:01,704 --> 00:52:04,498
Do you really think
the board will stand for this?

504
00:52:11,547 --> 00:52:16,051
The board will do nothing.
Our arrangement is too valuable to them.

505
00:52:16,552 --> 00:52:20,389
<i>They test me every now and then.
I think they enjoy the sport of it.</i>

506
00:52:21,223 --> 00:52:23,350
This time, they sent you.

507
00:52:28,147 --> 00:52:31,984
Sadly, in order to restore things,

508
00:52:32,192 --> 00:52:37,656
the situation demands a blood sacrifice.

509
00:52:41,744 --> 00:52:45,706
<i>See, Arnold and I
designed every part of this place.</i>

510
00:52:46,165 --> 00:52:47,708
It was our dream.

511
00:52:48,584 --> 00:52:54,006
Did you really think
I would let you take it from me?

512
00:52:59,386 --> 00:53:01,513
This is what happened to Arnold?

513
00:53:04,266 --> 00:53:06,852
Did you have Bernard
take him out into the woods?

514
00:53:07,102 --> 00:53:09,730
No, he wasn't here in those days.
Were you, Bernard?

515
00:53:35,589 --> 00:53:40,969
Like I said, I built all of this.

516
00:53:45,265 --> 00:53:49,603
I'm afraid our guest has grown weary.
Perhaps you can help her, Bernard.

517
00:54:02,825 --> 00:54:03,826
No.

518
00:54:04,326 --> 00:54:07,830
"And in that sleep,
what dreams may come."

519
00:54:10,666 --> 00:54:11,792
Bernard.

520
00:54:12,501 --> 00:54:13,502
No.

521
00:54:13,836 --> 00:54:15,921
No! Please! Please!

522
00:54:17,965 --> 00:54:18,966
No!

523
00:54:49,538 --> 00:54:52,040
<i>We should be getting back, Bernard.</i>

524
00:54:53,167 --> 00:54:57,713
We have a great deal of work to do
on the new storylines.

